data.content:
Use `Assert.IsInstanceOfType`:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
public void Create_ReturnsCorrectHandler()
{
    var factory = new HandlerFactory();
    var result = factory.Create("email");

    Assert.IsInstanceOfType(result, typeof(EmailHandler));
    Assert.AreEqual("email", ((EmailHandler)result).Type);
}
```

`Assert.IsInstanceOfType(object, Type)` checks the runtime type and gives a clearer failure message (e.g., *"Expected type: EmailHandler. Actual type: SmsHandler."*) versus a `NullReferenceException` or `InvalidCastException` from a failed hard cast.

If you don't need to check `.Type` afterward, you can drop the cast entirely — `IsInstanceOfType` alone covers the type assertion.
